# File: pref.prf
#
# This file has been modified to suit *my* tastes.  Delete this and rename
# 'preforig.prf' to 'pref.prf' to get the original defaults.
#
# Oh, and the font-***-old.prf files were done that way so that I don't have
# to put up with IBM graphics.  Just rename them to remove the '-old' part
# if you want those graphics...
#
# The various <realm>.prf files (and the ones like 'Mage.SC' [Sorcery/Chaos
# spells for Magi]) are the spell macro files I use.  They are set up for
# MS-DOS/Windows function key definitions - you'll have to get the proper
# escape sequences for the function keys on your machine on your own.
#
# If you turn off the use_old_target option, it's best to go through the
# spell pref files (and the targetting of @f2 missiles below) and either
# remove the '*t' (thus requiring manual targetting each time - yech! ;), or
# else move the '*t' to the end of the macro, from each targetted macro to
# avoid any possible problems.
#
# The <realm>.prf will load on their own, but that's only good for single-
# realm characters.  For multi-realm characters, you'll have to explicitly
# load the files in the '@' macro menu. [eg, load 'Priest.DS' for Death/
# Sorcery Priests]
#
# 'template.txt' is just that - a blank pref file that I fill in when I need
# to use a new realm combination...
#
# This file defines "default" actions of various kinds
#
# This file includes, if appropriate, various "sub-files"
#
# See "lib/help/command.txt" and "src/files.c" for more information.

